<li id="comment-5645" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
<div class="comment-author vcard"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/9c03413c9935b78a9ec4dac74659ad28?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=G' class='photo avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> <span class="fn n">Jan</span></div>
<div class="comment-meta">Posted February 12, 2015 at 3:19 pm <span class="meta-sep"> | </span> <a href="#comment-5645" title="Permalink to this comment">Permalink</a></div>
<div class="comment-content">
<p>Johan, ek weet regtig nie waar jy jou informasie kry nie, maar kyk na die geheel beeld en nie net die woord waaroor jy opgewonde raak nie,  ek is nie altyd reg met al my vertolkings nie, maar weet genoeg om weer te sê jy sit die pot ver mis,  wat my verstand te bowe gaan, is dat jy na n webtuiste gaan van erenstige gelowige mense die woord na aan die hart dra en jy kom dit probeer afbreek met jou bullshit.  Only Jesus has the keys to death, the scriptures say: (Rev 1:18) I am the one who lives. I was dead, but look. I am alive forever and ever! And I hold the keys of death and Hades. What is Hades? Hades is the Greek term loosely translated as hell in the New Testament. It is described as a prison with gates, bars, and locks, and its location is downward. In English usage the word &#8220;Hades&#8221; first appears around 1600, as a term used to explain the article in the Apostles&#8217; Creed, &#8220;He descended into hell&#8221;, where the place of waiting (the place of &#8220;the spirits in prison&#8221; into which Jesus is there affirmed to have gone after the Crucifixion, known as the Harrowing of Hell), needed to be distinguished from what had come to be more usually called &#8220;hell&#8221;, i.e. the place or state of those finally damned. (1Pe 3:19) Jesus then preached to the spirits that were being kept in prison. In this verse the word prison is used again. (Rev 2:10) Do not fear what you are about to suffer. Behold, the devil is about to throw some of you into prison, that you may be tested, and for ten days you will have tribulation. Be faithful unto death, and I will give you the crown of life.  Hades can be found in the following scriptures: (Acts 2:27) &#8216;For you will not abandon my soul to Hades, or let your Holy One see corruption. (Rev 6:8)  (Rev 20:12-15) .  vervolg</p>
</div>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
<li id="comment-5646" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
<div class="comment-author vcard"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/9c03413c9935b78a9ec4dac74659ad28?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=G' class='photo avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> <span class="fn n">Jan</span></div>
<div class="comment-meta">Posted February 12, 2015 at 3:21 pm <span class="meta-sep"> | </span> <a href="#comment-5646" title="Permalink to this comment">Permalink</a></div>
<div class="comment-content">
<p>Hell is also described as Sheol which is a Hebrew word. It is translated as hell, death, grave and destruction and &#8220;the pit.&#8221; Sheol describes the general home of the dead, a place where life no longer exists. Examples: (1Sa 2:6) The LORD kills and brings to life; he brings down to Sheol and raises up. (2Sa 22:6) (Job 7:9) (Job 17:13; 19) (Psa 9:17) This word is used in 65 versus of the bible, with absolute certainty. The term Perdition is also used in Christian theology: by definition a state of eternal punishment and damnation into which a sinful and unrepentant person passes after death. In the King James Version of the bible the term is used in 8 versus. Examples: (Php 1:28) And in nothing terrified by your adversaries: which is to them an evident token of perdition, but to you of salvation, and that of God. (2Th 2:3) (1Ti 6:9) (Heb 10:39) (2Pe 3:7) (Rev 17:8) (Rev 17:9) Anyone with wisdom can figure this out….In the scriptures, it has been pointed out that hell is thus a place of unrelenting everlasting fire, these two Greek words, “Gehenna” and Tartarus, translates &#8220;hell&#8221; or &#8220;the fires of hell,&#8221; and expresses the place of punishment for sinners, evil doers and the wicked. It is usually associated with the final judgment and depicted as being an eternal, unquenchable fire. The wording used would then suggest that the fires never go out, it burns for all eternity, it is impossible to suppress or destroy: Jesus will destroy all sinners, the wicket, the beast, false prophet, devil and demons in the fires of hell as well. (Mat 25:41) Then the king will say to the evil people on his left, &#8216;Get away from me. God has already decided that you will be punished.   vervolg</p>
</div>
